\begin_body

\begin_layout Standard
This note attempt to derive the radiation field intensity of spontaneous
 emission of a two-level quantum system using retarded Green's function
 formulation.
 In the weak coupling limit and zero temperature, we conclude an analytical
 expression for the intennsity that agrees with Fermi's golden rule.
 We want to compare this result against semiclassical calculation by Ehrenfest+
 method (see the method note).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The Setting
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Electromagnetic Fieldin in second quantization
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We start with the description of the electromagnetic field in terms of second
 qauntization
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\widehat{H}_{EM}=\sum_{k,\sigma_{k}}\hbar\omega_{k}\left(\widehat{a}_{k,\sigma_{k}}^{\dagger}\widehat{a}_{k,\sigma_{k}}+\frac{1}{2}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{a}_{\mathbf{k},\boldsymbol{\sigma}}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{a}_{\mathbf{k},\boldsymbol{\sigma}}^{\dagger}$
\end_inset

 are corresponding annihilation and creation operators of the photon at
 frequency mode 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{k}=c\left|\mathbf{k}\right|$
\end_inset

 and polarization vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\text{\sigma}}$
\end_inset

.
 The electronic field and magetic field can be represented in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{a}_{\mathbf{k},\boldsymbol{\sigma}}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{a}_{\mathbf{k},\boldsymbol{\sigma}}^{\dagger}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\widehat{\mathbf{E}}\left(\mathbf{r}\right)=i\sum_{\mathbf{k},\boldsymbol{\sigma}}\mathcal{E}_{k}\boldsymbol{\sigma}\left(\widehat{a}_{\mathbf{k},\boldsymbol{\sigma}}e^{i\mathbf{k}\cdot\mathbf{r}}-\widehat{a}_{\mathbf{k},\boldsymbol{\sigma}}^{\dagger}e^{-i\mathbf{k}\cdot\mathbf{r}}\right)\label{eq:E-operator}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\widehat{\mathbf{B}}\left(\mathbf{r}\right)=i\sum_{\mathbf{k},\boldsymbol{\sigma}}\mathcal{B}_{k}\mathbf{k}\times\boldsymbol{\sigma}\left(\widehat{a}_{\mathbf{k},\boldsymbol{\sigma}}e^{i\mathbf{k}\cdot\mathbf{r}}-\widehat{a}_{\mathbf{k},\boldsymbol{\sigma}}^{\dagger}e^{-i\mathbf{k}\cdot\mathbf{r}}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

with the magnitude in the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-dimensional volumn 
\begin_inset Formula $L^{n}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{E}_{k}=\sqrt{\frac{\hbar\omega_{k}}{2\epsilon_{0}L^{n}}},\label{eq: CalE_k}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{B}_{k}=\mathcal{E}_{k}/c.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here we take he simplist form of the electronâ€“radiation coupling:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\widehat{V}=-\int dr^{n}\widehat{\mathbf{P}}\left(\mathbf{r}\right)\cdot\widehat{\mathbf{E}}\left(\mathbf{r}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\mathbf{P}}\left(\mathbf{r}\right)$
\end_inset

 is the electronic dipole distribution operator.
 Also, we use the point dipole approximation for spatial distribution
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\widehat{\mathbf{P}}\left(\mathbf{r}\right)=\widehat{\mathbf{P}}\delta^{n}\left(\mathbf{r}\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

We can write down the coupling as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\widehat{V}=-i\sum_{\mathbf{k},\boldsymbol{\sigma}}\mathcal{E}_{k}\widehat{\mathbf{P}}\cdot\boldsymbol{\sigma}\left(\widehat{a}_{\mathbf{k},\boldsymbol{\sigma}}-\widehat{a}_{\mathbf{k},\boldsymbol{\sigma}}^{\dagger}\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By the density of state for photon, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sum_{\mathbf{k},\boldsymbol{\sigma}}\rightarrow\sum_{\boldsymbol{\sigma}}\int dk^{n}g\left(k\right)f\left(k\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $g\left(k\right)$
\end_inset

 is the number of 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-state per unit volumn:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
g\left(k\right)=\left(\frac{L}{2\pi}\right)^{n}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 The probability distribution that a photon is in state 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 is given by Bose-Einstein distribution:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f\left(k\right)=\frac{1}{e^{\hbar\omega_{k}/k_{B}T}-1}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

For simplicity, we consider the system is at zero temperature.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $T\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

, it turns out that Bose-Einstein distribution becomes equally distributed,
 that is the probability is the same for each state.
 So we may simply use
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
f\left(k\right)\rightarrow1 & \text{as} & T\rightarrow0
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

We also write the integral in the spherical coordinate 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\int dk^{n}=\int k^{n-1}dk\int d\Omega^{n},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\int d\Omega^{n}=\begin{cases}
\int\sin\theta d\theta d\phi & n=3\\
\int d\phi & n=2\\
1 & n=1
\end{cases}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and end it up with
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sum_{\mathbf{k},\boldsymbol{\sigma}}\rightarrow\left(\frac{L}{2\pi}\right)^{n}\sum_{\boldsymbol{\sigma}}\int k^{n-1}dk\int d\Omega^{n}.\label{eq:SumToIntegral}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Hamiltonian in dressed state representation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We consider a simple quantum mechanical model capable to capture spontaneous
 emission: an electronic excited state 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|e\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 decays to extronic ground state 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|g\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 and emits photons into the radiation field.
 The system Hamiltonian is therefore:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\widehat{H}_{s}=E_{g}\left|g\right\rangle \left\langle g\right|+E_{e}\left|e\right\rangle \left\langle e\right|
\end{equation}

\end_inset

In the dressed state representation, we can dress the ground state and the
 excited state with ONE emission photon denoted as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left|g,0,\cdots,1_{\mathbf{k},\boldsymbol{\sigma}},\cdots,0\right\rangle \equiv\left|g,\mathbf{k}\boldsymbol{\sigma}\right\rangle 
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left|e,0,\cdots,1_{\mathbf{k},\boldsymbol{\sigma}},\cdots,0\right\rangle \equiv\left|e,\mathbf{k}\boldsymbol{\sigma}\right\rangle ,
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|0,\cdots,1_{\mathbf{k},\boldsymbol{\sigma}},\cdots,0\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 is the fock state of photon representing one emitting photon of frequency
 mode 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{k}=c\left|\vec{k}\right|$
\end_inset

 and polarization vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\sigma}$
\end_inset

.
 The ground state and the excited state in vacuum are denoted as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left|g,0,\cdots,0\right\rangle \equiv\left|g,0\right\rangle ,
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left|e,0,\cdots,0\right\rangle \equiv\left|e,0\right\rangle .
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that we are restricted in the Hilbert space of one photon emission.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left\langle g,\mathbf{k}\boldsymbol{\sigma}\right|\widehat{V}\left|e,0\right\rangle =\left\langle e,\mathbf{k}\boldsymbol{\sigma}\right|\widehat{V}\left|g,0\right\rangle =V_{1k}=i\mathcal{E}_{k}\boldsymbol{\mu}\cdot\boldsymbol{\sigma}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the transition dipole moment of the two level system is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left\langle e\right|\widehat{\mathbf{P}}\left|g\right\rangle =\left\langle e\right|\widehat{\mathbf{P}}\left|g\right\rangle =\boldsymbol{\mu}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The Hamiltonian can be written in matrix representation
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
H=\left(\begin{array}{cccc}
E_{e} & \begin{array}{ccc}
\cdots & i\mathcal{E}_{k}\boldsymbol{\mu}\cdot\boldsymbol{\sigma} & \cdots\end{array}\\
\begin{array}{c}
\vdots\\
-i\mathcal{E}_{k}\boldsymbol{\mu}\cdot\boldsymbol{\sigma}\\
\vdots
\end{array} & \boxed{\begin{array}{ccc}
\ddots\\
 & E_{g}+\hbar\omega_{k}\\
 &  & \ddots
\end{array}}\\
 &  & E_{g} & \begin{array}{ccc}
\cdots & i\mathcal{E}_{k}\boldsymbol{\mu}\cdot\boldsymbol{\sigma} & \cdots\end{array}\\
 &  & \begin{array}{c}
\vdots\\
-i\mathcal{E}_{k}\boldsymbol{\mu}\cdot\boldsymbol{\sigma}\\
\vdots
\end{array} & \boxed{\begin{array}{ccc}
\ddots\\
 & E_{e}+\hbar\omega_{k}\\
 &  & \ddots
\end{array}}
\end{array}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Note that we assume there is no explict coupling between electronic states
 in this model.
 The excited state only couples to the ground states via the radiation field.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The total wavefunction can be written in 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left|\psi\left(t\right)\right\rangle =c_{0}\left(t\right)\left|e,0\right\rangle +\sum_{k}c_{\mathbf{k}\boldsymbol{\sigma}}\left(t\right)\left|g,\mathbf{k}\boldsymbol{\sigma}\right\rangle +d_{0}\left(t\right)\left|g,0\right\rangle +\sum_{k}d_{\mathbf{k}\boldsymbol{\sigma}}\left(t\right)\left|e,\mathbf{k}\boldsymbol{\sigma}\right\rangle 
\end{equation}

\end_inset

i.e.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left|\psi\left(t\right)\right\rangle =\left(\begin{array}{c}
c_{0}\\
\vdots\\
c_{\mathbf{k}\boldsymbol{\sigma}}\\
\vdots\\
d_{0}\\
\vdots\\
d_{\mathbf{k}\boldsymbol{\sigma}}\\
\vdots
\end{array}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

We consider the initioal condition is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left|\psi\left(0\right)\right\rangle =c_{0}\left(0\right)\left|e,0\right\rangle +d_{0}\left(0\right)\left|g,0\right\rangle 
\end{equation}

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|c_{0}\left(0\right)\right|^{2}+\left|d_{0}\left(0\right)\right|^{2}=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Retarded Green's Function Formulation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since the Hamilonian for 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 is decoupled, we can propagate them independently.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

-part are non-resonant, we take the first order approximation
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
d_{0}\left(t\right)=d_{0}\left(0\right)e^{-iE_{g}t/\hbar}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
d_{\mathbf{k}\boldsymbol{\sigma}}\left(t\right)=0
\end{equation}

\end_inset

For 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

-part, we need to use retarded Green's function.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Definitions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By the retarded Green's function, the time evolution of the total wavefunction
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\psi\left(t\right)\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 can expressed as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left|\psi\left(t\right)\right\rangle =-\frac{1}{2\pi i}\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}dEe^{-i\left(E+i\eta\right)t/\hbar}\widehat{G}\left(E\right)\left|\psi\left(0\right)\right\rangle .
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the retarded Green's operator is defined as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\widehat{G}\left(E\right)=\frac{1}{E-\widehat{H}+i\eta},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta\rightarrow0^{+}$
\end_inset

 is a small real number closes to zero.
 We write the Hamiltonian is the form of 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{H}=\widehat{H}^{0}+\widehat{V}$
\end_inset

, so that the Green's function of 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{H}^{0}$
\end_inset

 is unperturbed:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
G_{11}^{0}\left(E\right)=\left\langle 1\right|\widehat{G}^{0}\left(E\right)\left|1\right\rangle =\frac{1}{E-E_{1}+i\eta},
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
G_{kk}^{0}\left(E\right)=\left\langle k\right|\widehat{G}^{0}\left(E\right)\left|k\right\rangle =\frac{1}{E-E_{k}+i\eta}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

By using the Dyson's identity,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\widehat{G}=\widehat{G}^{0}+\widehat{G}^{0}\widehat{V}\widehat{G}=\widehat{G}^{0}+\widehat{G}\widehat{V}\widehat{G}^{0}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

we have a self-consistent expression for the full Green's function:
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
G_{11}=G_{11}^{0}+\sum_{\ell}G_{11}^{0}V_{1\ell}G_{\ell1}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
G_{1k}=\sum_{\ell}G_{11}^{0}V_{1\ell}G_{\ell k}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
G_{k1}=G_{kk}^{0}V_{k1}G_{11}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
G_{kk^{\prime}}=G_{kk^{\prime}}^{0}+G_{kk}^{0}V_{k1}G_{1k^{\prime}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
G_{11}\left(E\right)=\frac{G_{11}^{0}}{1-G_{11}^{0}\sum_{\ell}\left|V_{1\ell}\right|^{2}G_{\ell\ell}^{0}}=\frac{1}{E-E_{1}+i\eta-\sum_{\ell}\frac{\left|V_{1\ell}\right|^{2}}{E-E_{\ell}+i\eta}}\label{eq:G11}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
G_{k1}\left(E\right)=\frac{V_{k1}}{E-E_{k}+i\eta}\frac{1}{E-E_{1}+i\eta-\sum_{\ell}\frac{\left|V_{1\ell}\right|^{2}}{E-E_{\ell}+i\eta}},\label{eq:Gk1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $k,\ell$
\end_inset

 denote the quantum number for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}\boldsymbol{\sigma}$
\end_inset

 for convenience.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
How to get Fermi's golden rule?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:SumToIntegral"

\end_inset

 and Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:V1k"

\end_inset

, we have (change the dummy variable to 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

)
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sum_{\ell}\frac{\left|V_{1\ell}\right|^{2}}{E-E_{\ell}+i\eta}=\left(\frac{L}{2\pi}\right)^{n}\sum_{\boldsymbol{\sigma}}\int k^{n-1}dk\int d\Omega^{n}\left|\boldsymbol{\mu}\cdot\boldsymbol{\sigma}\right|^{2}\frac{\mathcal{E}_{k}^{2}}{E-E_{k}+i\eta}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\mu}=\mu\hat{\mathbf{z}}$
\end_inset

 and the spherical angle integration can be carried out by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\sum_{\boldsymbol{\sigma}}\int d\Omega^{n}\left|\boldsymbol{\mu}\cdot\boldsymbol{\sigma}\right|^{2} & = & \mu^{2}\sum_{\boldsymbol{\sigma}}\int d\Omega^{n}\left|\hat{\mathbf{z}}\cdot\boldsymbol{\sigma}\right|^{2}\\
 & \equiv & \mu^{2}\cdot{\cal A}_{n}.
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where we define:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
{\cal A}_{n}=\begin{cases}
2\int\sin\theta d\theta d\phi\cos^{2}\theta=\frac{8\pi}{3} & n=3\\
2\int\cos^{2}\phi d\phi=2\pi & n=2\\
2 & n=1
\end{cases}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Note that the factor of 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{\sigma_{k}}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The radial integration is carried out by Cauchy integral identity (using
 Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq: CalE_k"

\end_inset

)
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\int k^{n-1}dk\left(\frac{L}{2\pi}\right)^{n}\frac{\mathcal{E}_{k}^{2}}{E-E_{k}+i\eta} & = & \frac{1}{2\epsilon_{0}}\left(\frac{1}{2\pi\hbar c}\right)^{n}\int E_{k}^{n-1}dE_{k}\frac{E_{k}-E_{0}}{E-E_{k}+i\eta}\\
 & = & -\frac{i\pi}{2\epsilon_{0}}\left(\frac{E-E_{0}}{2\pi\hbar c}\right)^{n}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{k}=E_{0}+\hbar\omega_{k}=E_{0}+\hbar ck$
\end_inset

 and the principal value term is eliminated.
 Therefore, this yields a simple expression for 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sum_{\ell}\frac{\left|V_{1\ell}\right|^{2}}{E-E_{\ell}+i\eta}=-\frac{i}{2}\frac{\pi\mu^{2}}{\epsilon_{0}}{\cal A}_{n}\left(\frac{E-E_{0}}{2\pi\hbar c}\right)^{n}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

In the weak coupling limit, where Fermi's golden rule is valid, we can argue
 that Green's function, Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:G11"

\end_inset

 and Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Gk1"

\end_inset

, is expected to be a sharp peak at 
\begin_inset Formula $E=E_{1}$
\end_inset

, thus we can assume only the value near resonance contribute in the above
 equation and becomes independent of 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sum_{\ell}\frac{\left|V_{1\ell}\right|^{2}}{E-E_{\ell}+i\eta}\approx-\frac{i}{2}\frac{\pi\mu^{2}}{\epsilon_{0}}{\cal A}_{n}\left(\frac{E_{1}-E_{0}}{2\pi\hbar c}\right)^{n}\equiv-\frac{i}{2}\Gamma_{1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

For convenience, we denote 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Gamma^{\left(n\right)}\left(E_{1}\right)=\Gamma_{1}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

